<h4 align="left">
    <strong>
        <span style="color:red">GLMMadaptive package</span>
    </strong>
</h4>
<ul style="list-style-type:circle">
<li> Function <a href="https://goo.gl/KyiDVB" target="_blank">mixed_model()</a> fits 
  generalized linear mixed effects models for clustered data; main arguments:
  <ul style="list-style-type:square">
  <li><font face="Courier New">fixed</font> and <font face="Courier New">random</font>: 
  Formulas specifying the fixed- and random-effects parts of the model. For the latter, it
  should only contain the right-hand side part, e.g., 
  <font face="Courier New">~ time | id</font>, where time is a variable, and 
  <font face="Courier New">id</font> the grouping factor. When the symbol 
  <font face="Courier New">||</font> is used in the definition of this argument (instead 
  of <font face="Courier New">|</font>), then the covariance matrix of the random effects 
  is assumed to be diagonal. Some examples:
        <table style="width:100%" aling="center">
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Description</strong></td>
                <td><strong>mixed_model() syntax</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>random intercepts</td>
                <td><font face="Courier New">mixed_model(fixed = y ~ time, random = ~ 1 | id)</font></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>random intercepts & random slopes</td>
                <td><font face="Courier New">mixed_model(fixed = y ~ time, random = ~ time | id)</font></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>random intercepts & slopes diagonal covariance matrix</td>
                <td><font face="Courier New">mixed_model(fixed = y ~ time, random = ~ time || id)</font></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>random intercepts & nonlinear slopes with splines and diagonal covariance matrix</td>
                <td><font face="Courier New">mixed_model(fixed = y ~ time, random = ~ ns(time, 2) || id)</font></td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <br/>
        </li>
  <li><font face="Courier New">family</font>: a 
        <a href="https://goo.gl/4EicoR" target="_blank">family</a> object providing a 
        description of the error distribution and link function to be used in the 
        model.</li>
    <li><font face="Courier New">data</font>: a 
        <a href="https://goo.gl/PVVYyn" target="_blank">data frame</a> that contains the 
        aforementioned variables.</li>
    <li><font face="Courier New">nAGQ</font>: integer scalar - the number of points per 
        axis for evaluating the adaptive Gauss-Hermite approximation to the 
        log-likelihood. Defaults to 11.
    </li>
  </ul>
</li>

<br/>

<li>Function <a href="https://goo.gl/KyiDVB" target="_blank">anova()</a> can be
  used to peform likelihood ratio tests between nested generalized mixed effects models.</li>
</ul>


<h4 align="left">
    <strong>
        <span style="color:red">lme4 package</span>
    </strong>
</h4>
<ul style="list-style-type:circle">
  <li> Function <a href="https://goo.gl/U7tf8T" target="_blank">glmer()</a> fits 
  generalized linear mixed effects models for clustered data; main arguments:
  <ul style="list-style-type:square">
    <li>
        <font face="Courier New">formula</font>: describing both the 
        fixed-effects and random-effects part of the model, with the response on the left 
        of a <font face="Courier New">"~"</font> operator and the terms, separated by 
        <font face="Courier New">"+"</font> operators, on the 
        right. Random-effects terms are distinguished by vertical bars 
        (<font face="Courier New">"|"</font>) separating expressions for design matrices 
        from grouping factors. Two vertical bars (<font face="Courier New">"||"</font>) 
        can be used to specify multiple uncorrelated random effects for the same grouping 
        variable. Some examples:
        <table style="width:100%" aling="center">
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Description</strong></td>
                <td><strong>glmer() syntax</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>random intercepts</td>
                <td><font face="Courier New">glmer(y ~ time + (1 | id))</font></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>random intercepts & slopes diagonal covariance matrix</td>
                <td><font face="Courier New">glmer(y ~ time + (time || id))</font></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>nested random intercepts</td>
                <td><font face="Courier New">glmer(y ~ time + (1 | id / eye))</font></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>crossed random intercepts</td>
                <td><font face="Courier New">glmer(y ~ time + (1 | id) + (1 | visit))</font></td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <br/>
    </li>
    <li>
        <font face="Courier New">family</font>: a 
        <a href="https://goo.gl/4EicoR" target="_blank">family</a> object providing a 
        description of the error distribution and link function to be used in the model.
    </li>
    <li>
        <font face="Courier New">data</font>: a 
        <a href="https://goo.gl/PVVYyn" target="_blank">data frame</a> that contains the 
        aforementioned variables.
    </li>
        <li>
        <font face="Courier New">nAGQ</font>: integer scalar - the number of points per 
        axis for evaluating the adaptive Gauss-Hermite approximation to the 
        log-likelihood. Defaults to 1, corresponding to the Laplace approximation.
    </li>

  </ul>
  </li>
  
  <br/>
  
  <li>Function <a href="https://goo.gl/U7tf8T" target="_blank">anova()</a> can be
  used to peform likelihood ratio tests between nested generalized mixed effects models.
  </li>
  <br/>
</ul>
